<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Stack-unit service</p>
    <h2>Stack washer-dryers fit operations where floor space is the constraint, not throughput.</h2>

    <p>A commercial stack unit is a stacked washer plus dryer in a single tower form-factor, sized 18 to 30 lb per machine. The form factor is what defines the use case: small apartment building common-area laundry rooms (4 to 24 units sharing two stacks), small bars and restaurants doing in-house kitchen-towel laundry, salon and spa spaces, fitness studios washing yoga mats and towels, vacation rental managers handling turnover laundry. Limited daily cycles (5 to 10 per machine typical), small operation use, but commercial-grade equipment because residential machines wouldn't survive the cycle count.</p>

    <p>Our techs service the full commercial stack lineup across LA County, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. <strong>Speed Queen Quantum SC30 stack</strong> (Alliance Laundry, the most common LA commercial stack). <strong>Maytag Commercial Laundry stack</strong> (Whirlpool Corp, mid-tier). <strong>Huebsch stack</strong> (Alliance Laundry value tier, sister to Speed Queen). Stack units mount the dryer above the washer in a single tower, sharing the footprint of one machine.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. <strong>BHGS #A49573</strong> license. <strong>EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410</strong>. <strong></strong> scope for adjacent gas dryer and laundry room HVAC. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Parent: <a href="/commercial/washer-repair/">commercial washer repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Common scenarios</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Top stack-unit repairs in our 5-county territory.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Door interlock switches (year 4 to 7).</strong> Stack units have two doors, two interlocks; cycles add up at the apartment-building common-area scale. $260 to $420 per door.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain pump (washer side).</strong> Lint plus residue from mixed loads. $360 to $540.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating element (electric dryer side).</strong> Year 5 to 8 typical wear. $340 to $580.</li>
      <li><strong>Igniter (gas dryer side).</strong> Year 5 to 8 wear. $260 to $440.</li>
      <li><strong>Drum thermistor drift.</strong> Causes dryer to short-cycle on false-high reading, takes 3 cycles to dry. $220 to $360.</li>
      <li><strong>Belt drive (washer and dryer separate belts).</strong> Year 4 to 6 typical wear on each. $240 to $360 per belt.</li>
      <li><strong>Vent restriction service (dryer side).</strong> Lint accumulation in shorter exhaust runs. $200 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket and boot seal (washer side).</strong> Year 5 to 8 wear. $260 to $440.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Field observations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three things we see on stack-unit calls that aren't in the property manager's binder.</h2>

    <p><strong>1. Apartment-building stacks see lower cycles per day than the manufacturer expected, but rougher tenant abuse.</strong> A stack unit in a 12-unit building's common-area laundry sees maybe 5 to 8 cycles per day total. That's well below the equipment's rated daily throughput. But tenant abuse (overloading, mixing inappropriate items, running with foreign objects in pockets) drives drain pump and door-interlock failures earlier than the cycle count would predict. The fix isn't more service: it's clearer signage in the laundry room about load limits and what not to wash, plus periodic reminders.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Vent restriction on stack dryers shows up as "takes 3 cycles to dry" before it shows up as overheating.</strong> The 4-inch exhaust vent on a stack dryer is shorter than a side-by-side configuration, but it still clogs with lint. The first symptom is reduced dryer efficiency: tenants complain the dryer takes longer, building manager bumps the cycle time, energy bill rises. Eventually the dryer hits high-limit thermal cutoff and shuts down mid-cycle. Annual vent cleaning ($200 to $340) prevents the cascade.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Property managers benefit from annual maintenance contracts more than one-off repair.</strong> Multi-building property management accounts that schedule annual maintenance ($280 to $440 per stack unit) get fewer emergency callouts and longer equipment life. The math works out positively: one prevented emergency dispatch ($120 plus parts) covers most of the annual maintenance cost across the building's fleet. We offer multi-building contract pricing for property management accounts.</p>
  </div>
</section>

